04578nam a22006735i 9781845459284DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818454592847 a10.1515/97818454592842doi  a(DE-B1597)636454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aLA721.82 .P83 2009 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a370.943090451 aPuaca, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLearning Democracy :bEducation Reform in West Germany, 1945-1965 /cBrian Puaca. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMonographs in German History ;v2700tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter 1 REBUILDING EDUCATION IN A “NEW SPIRIT” The Challenges of the Immediate Postwar Period, 1945–1947 -- tChapter 2 “WE LEARNED WHAT DEMOCRACY REALLY MEANT” New Experiences Inside and Outside the Classroom, 1948–1954 -- tChapter 3 POLITICAL EDUCATION Reforms Continue Beneath the Surface, 1955–1959 -- tChapter 4 REFORM REIGNITED Ambitious Eff orts in the New Decade, 1960–1965 -- tCONCLUSION -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScholarship on the history of West Germany’s educational system has traditionally portrayed the postwar period of Allied occupation as a failure and the following decades as a time of pedagogical stagnation. Two decades after World War II, however, the Federal Republic had become a stable democracy, a member of NATO, and a close ally of the West. Had the schools really failed to contribute to this remarkable transformation of German society and political culture? This study persuasively argues that long before the protest movements of the late 1960s, the West German educational system was undergoing meaningful reform from within. Although politicians and intellectual elites paid little attention to education after 1945, administrators, teachers, and pupils initiated significant changes in schools at the local level. The work of these actors resulted in an array of democratic reforms that signaled a departure from the authoritarian and nationalistic legacies of the past. The establishment of exchange programs between the United States and West Germany, the formation of student government organizations and student newspapers, the publication of revised history and civics textbooks, the expansion of teacher training programs, and the creation of a Social Studies curriculum all contributed to the advent of a new German educational system following World War II. The subtle, incremental reforms inaugurated during the first two postwar decades prepared a new generation of young Germans for their responsibilities as citizens of a democratic state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEducation and statezGermany (West)xHistory. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszGermany (West)xHistory. 0aEducational changezGermany (West)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184545928440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781845459284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781845459284/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK